segments.text: Because I have to be at a meeting at 3, so I've got to leave at about 1 in Austin.
Oh, oh, oh.
Then we will have to go until 1.
When your freshman year, when you were going to go home, how did you get back and forth?
How did you travel?
Hitchhike.
Describe Aggie hitchhiking.
Uniform and a maroon and white bag that said TAM on it and
Just as good as having a car.
And where did you catch your ride from College Station?
Where did you?
Out here on 21.
I'd go to Somerville and then back through La Grange and then get on 77.
Or I'd go to 21 all the way to 77 up there and get back.
I never had.
I could get home hitchhiking almost the exact same time that I could get home with a car.
Did you ever have any negative experience hitchhiking?
Uh-uh.
Well, I had one guy.
I had one guy who was an older Hispanic guy, and he had just bought a purple Pontiac Catalina.
And I was going to A&I to see my girlfriend at the time, and he picked me up in LaGrange.
He said, you're in the Army?
I said, no, I'm in A&M.
He said, well, where are you going?
And I said, well, as far as you'll go, but I need to go all the way to Kingsville.
He said, well, I'll go to Kingsville.
I just bought this car, and I got a case of Jack's beer in the back, and why don't we just go to Kingsville?
And I said, golly, if that's okay with you.
We were using up most of two lanes getting down there.
We got there, and he got to Kingsville.
He was a great guy.
Got to Kingsville, turned around, and going back to Giddings.
Now, did the hitchhiking routine continue throughout your four years for students in general?
Yeah.
Well, I finally got my senior year, I got my sister's car that was new when she went to UT, so it was five years old when I got it.
But it was still, hitchhiking was still going on.
Oh, yeah.
You bet.
The...
On this all-male campus, how did you and your buddies get dates, or almost all-male?
Oh, we usually didn't.
Well, we were a little bit lucky in that one of the guys in our outfit couldn't handle all this stuff, and he went to Stephen F. Austin.
and became a disc jockey in Stephen F. Austin, somewhat of a celebrity.
And so he would call us on a pretty regular basis and have us come up to Nacogdoches and visit with him.
And then I had friends at the University of Texas, TU, so we'd go there and get dates there.
But my first couple of years, I was dating this girl from A&I, and so she would always come up and I'd always
Always go down there, but... Where did a date like that stay when she was here?
Where did she spend the night?
In a hotel.
Okay.
Because no longer was it normal for them to spend the night with a faculty... Yeah, no.
That was gone.
It was just hotel room.
One of these hotels around here, they were...
Were the tests still coming down in large numbers?
I guess about my freshman year, and it kind of started...
When I was a senior, when I was a junior, the Aggie sweetheart, or whatever you call it, was still from TWU.
When I was a senior, we changed that in student government and made it local.
Describe how that change came about.
That's an important point.
Well, actually,
I did it, we did it through student government.
We just decided it was time and so when my senior year in student government, we passed the deal.
I remember going to TWU and just saying, you know, we're getting so big now and it's becoming offensive to ladies here and stuff like that and we're going to do it there.
And so we just did and I put a guy named David Moore in charge of, you know,
deal.
He's a stockbroker now in Tyler.
And I'm sure it was quite coincidental that the girl that became the first Aggie sweetheart from here is now his wife.
And his daughter is a student here now.
How did the women at TWU respond, react to the decision?
I think okay.
I think some of them were not too happy, but it wasn't a bad visit.
I remember going up there and
explaining to them that we were going to do this.
And the student senate at the time of that decision was entirely all male?
No.
There were some women in there?
Was there much disagreement with the decision?
Almost none.
It was just time.
Let's talk about campus administrative leadership.
Describe Earl Rudder as you and your buddies saw him.
Well, see, he died, I think, when I was maybe the end of my freshman year.
You came in fall of 68?
When did he die?
Early 70.
Early 70?
So at the end of my sophomore year, something like that.
Well, I only got to see him one time because I was, I mean, I was sophomore class president and class presidents didn't,
get in that realm.
I knew Jack Williams obviously a lot better.
Earl Rudder was viewed as a god.
He really was.
All you heard was stories about Omaha and Earl Rudder.
He was generally viewed as the guy that saved A&M, but the core
If he was viewed as a guy that diversified A&M, he was also, because of his war record, the Corps just revered him.
Nobody I knew ever met the man, but he was just like a god to all.
Did you all think that anybody could argue with him or protest?
No.
We didn't do protests.
I remember during that time there were a lot of protests on campuses.
When Jack Williams first came in, his first day, first night here, there was about 10 of us.
It was a corps commander, a committee of about five people and students in it.
I was one of them.
Kent was one of them and several others.
And we must have put 2,000 people in his front yard.
I'm sure he looked out there and thought, oh, my God, here I am right in the middle of,
you know, a student protest and it was just us welcoming him to A&M.
I remember the media were pretty shocked that you'd have a student demonstration welcoming a new president to A&M.
What did describe Jack Williams as you and other students understood him?
Real smart.
Real smart guy.
I mean, he was a real no nonsense guy.
Didn't take very long.
I remember we were setting up something... What's that professor's name?
He's like a physical... Wehmeyer...
He was vice president for academic affairs during Williams' time.
Oh, Dick Winerdi.
Winerdi, yeah.
Anyway, we had decided we wanted something called a disciplinary appeals
where you couldn't just kick a kid out of school.
You had to at least have somebody review it and stuff like that, and we'd worked all this stuff out with Winerdi.
And I remember the meeting with Williams lasted about 4.2 minutes.
He said, fine, did it, done.
He didn't tarry around too long with his decisions.
He knew what he wanted to do.
What about him as a public speaker?
Well, I thought he was good.
I saw him at a...
I went with him.
particularly my senior year, travel with him to listen to a lot of his speeches and sometimes the two of us to do one from the student perspective and stuff like that.
I thought he was a great public speaker.
Describe from that year when you were student body president, describe some of those trips.
Well, we would go to, I remember one time we went to, it was like a Rotary Club or a Lions Club or somewhere.
I think it was in Texarkana.
I'm not real sure.
But I remember the guy gets up
I had already said a little blurb about A&M and the guy gets up and introduces Dr. Williams with an Aggie joke.
And Williams, I mean the guy, by the time Williams finished within the first five minutes, the guy I'm sure just got on his all fours and crawled out.
It was just, you know, terrible.
That didn't happen anymore.
That got around pretty good.
But what Williams could do is,

For those, he's so cerebral, for those people that, you know, mistakenly thought A&M was a bunch of clodbusters and stuff like that, all of a sudden you listen to that guy's speeches, boy, that's a whole new image of what they were used to.
So I think one of the things he added a lot to was,
He made us this national presence academically.
Did an awful lot for that.
Did you ever go with him to anything political?
Like political fundraisers and stuff like that?
Or to Austin to a hearing or anything like that?
Oh, one time.
Yeah, just a little show-off deal where they took some students with them before Senate Finance Committee and wanted to have plenty of short hair.
haircuts and stuff like that, so I went to a few, maybe one or two of those.
How skillful was he with the real world politicians?
The what?
How skillful was he with politicians?
Oh, he was good.
He was good.
He was really good at all of it.
He didn't, I mean, Heatley never liked him, and that wasn't going to change.
I don't know what caused that, but once you cross Heatley, it doesn't ever change.
I know Heatley real well, and if Heatley buries the hatchet, he always remembers where he buried the hatchet.
He was like that.
But, no, he was good.
I think the appropriations during that period of time were some of their better clips.
Of course, it didn't hurt at that time to have, you know, the chairman of the State Affairs Committee in the Senate, a member of the Budget Board.
Bill Preston was chairman of the House Appropriations Committee.
Bill Clayton was Speaker of the House of Representatives.
I mean, that don't hurt too bad.
Yeah, yeah.
And let's see, Conley had finished his, who was the governor at that point?
Briscoe.
Briscoe, Briscoe.
And he had Reagan Brown there doing all of the A&M stuff.
Back to campus student life.
Here's one that I haven't asked many people.
Do junior buddies know about any steam tunnels?
Sure.
Describe steam tunnels and what went on in steam tunnels.
We didn't do it for any illicit purposes.
There were some rumors that people would use them to try to get into you guys' offices where you had tests and stuff like that, but we thought that was more easily done by simply scaling the walls.
No, we would just go in them, not as freshmen and sophomores because they never would let us out for stuff like that, but
Yeah, on weekends when there was nothing to do, no football season going on, we'd go into the Stephen Tunnels and just wander and see where we came out.
Where did you normally enter, though?
Over by the academic building.
Okay, and you could go how far?
To the other end of campus, best I could tell.
To engineering, to Zachary?
Oh, see, that was just being built down there.
I remember when I was a...
When I was a senior is when they dedicated to Zacherville, and I remember that dedication.
Could you go to the MSC?
Yeah, right up to it.
Yeah.
Yeah, I think you could kind of go pretty much everywhere.
I mean, I'm sure there's skeletons down there somewhere where somebody never got out.
And you used flashlights?
Uh-huh.
Because there's no lights in the tunnel.
No.
And about how, what are the dimensions of the tunnels?
Oh, well, you can, you can, you know, stand up straight, but you've got to kind of hunch over a little bit to get through.
And there's a bunch of wires and pipes in it.
How wide?
Oh, as wide as that door, maybe, maybe a little less.
And were there any unwritten rules about who was not to be in the tunnels?
Nah, we just lifted up the grate.
Was it by and large, though, core primarily?
Well, every time I went in, I'm sure there were other kids that did the same thing, but we would go in and just kind of see how lost we could get and see where we came up.
And there'd be a fork in the deal and one group would go one place and we'd find out where we were.
Now, when you were student body president your senior year, would that have been acceptable for you to be in the steam tunnel?
Nah, that wouldn't have been very good.
Okay, so.
It wouldn't have been very good.
Do you have any information or rumors about secret fraternities that you can share with this machine?
No.
I always heard those rumors, little snippets of them, but I don't know anything about them.
You don't know anything about them?
No.
Of all the people I've asked, only John Lindsay has admitted that he
was a member, and they did exist.
The only thing that I was a member of, anything like that, was something called the Fine Guys Association that Ed Cooper started.

And Ed Cooper and Kent Caperton and Roger Miller and I and Chet Edwards and a whole bunch of guys under Cooper's great direction founded the Fine Guys Association, which best I could tell, primary purpose was to drink beer.
And we would always do that at Peggy and Ed's house.
And then Ed would try to get us home.
So y'all didn't get into much trouble.
No.
Were there any world important off-campus events while you were a student here?
Vietnam War the whole time.
Everybody was real concerned about that.
I mean, all of us that were in the Corps just assumed
You know, we had a couple choices.
We could quit school and go in as a private or we could stay and go in as a lieutenant and we decided we're going to go in as a lieutenant and try to see if we can survive that way.
I remember being in a hall the night that Nixon drew the lottery and, you know, as everybody's number was called, they would groan and go to bed.
And did you guys ever talk about what it might be like to go over there?
Oh yeah, because we knew people that would come back from campus all the time and would go into our military science classes and tell us what was going on over there and stuff like that.
And there was no demonstration here against the war was there?
Zero.
If there would have been a demonstration on this campus, it would have been for it.
If there was opposition to it, which I'm sure there was, it never surfaced at all.
I was trying to think of, like everybody knows where they were when they heard that Kennedy had been shot or D-Day or Pearl Harbor, but there was no event like that.
What about the moon landing?
I was just getting out of high school.
Let's see.
Student indulgences.
Where did students go on a Saturday night to have a wild time?
Ralph's Pizza.
That's all we had.
Where were the favorite beer halls?
Ralph's Pizza.
Was Sparky's yet at Eastgate?
I don't remember that.
Ralph's Pizza was a place over here on, it's not there anymore.
And Uncle Ed's was gone.
I don't remember Uncle Ed.
Down Welborn Road, there was a place run by a Czech named Hrdlicka, H-Y-R-D-L-Y-C-K-A, but it was pronounced Hardlickers.
Oh, really?
And that, 20 years before you were here, that was where you could walk down about a half mile.
No, Rouse Pizza's about all we had, and then there was a couple of dance halls, Lakeview and Deanville, but that's if you just wanted to go get beat up.
I remember Kent Caperton...
afforded me that opportunity one night in Deanville.
He goes over and picks a fight with some guy about three times, of course, everybody's three times bigger in Caperton.
And the guy said, well, you're too little to fight.
I said, yeah, I know, but I brought my friend.
We didn't stay very long.
Did any of your friends ever go buy anything at Whiskey Bridge?
When I was here, out of Highway 6, there was a little series of liquor stores.
Well, 60, straight west towards Snook, just across the bridge.
I don't know.
I remember hearing about Whiskey Bridge.
Where we always went to buy our whiskey was straight out of Highway 6.
There was a place on the right before it all got voted in here, and we'd just get it all from there.
Let's go back to athletic times.
Describe your going on a court trip.
Did you go as a freshman?
Uh-huh.
Where?
We usually did two a year.
It was usually Houston.
Austin was usually one of them, obviously, every other year.
And then Houston was one.
And Fort Worth usually was one.
Dallas.
How did you get up there?
But we'd go with somebody that had a car.
Where would you stay?
A cheap hotel.
Okay.
And then what would y'all do on Friday night?
We would what you call drink whiskey and drink beer.
And, you know, everybody would usually have a date for something like that.
How did you get those dates?
Oh, well, mine usually came from Kingsville.
Oh, so you're...
Yeah, or somebody, there was a whole bunch of fixing up, too.
I mean, somebody from Dallas, oh, I've got, you know, a sister with 10 friends or something like that, and so that was a... Do you remember any court trip anecdotes that are worth sharing?
No, just trying to remember them is a real challenge.
Amusing or goofy or... No.
What if you literally couldn't go on that court trip?
Was there any punishment?
When, on Monday?
I don't know of anybody that never, that missed it.
I don't think it was an optional deal.
I mean, you had to be pretty, pretty sick.
That was a, yeah.
And how did the spectators on the street respond to the chorus?
I was always shocked.
You know, I never was big on parades.
I wouldn't go to, you know, it's kind of like rodeos, you know, once you've been to one, once you've ridden in one, why do you want to go again?
But it was,
Oh, it was just real uplifting, I guess is the best word, to go through Houston and see people ten deep just there for the Corps and the band.

And Austin, you know, I remember the first time I ever went to the Corps trip in Austin, I thought, well, God, these people are going to be throwing stuff at us, but there's so many darn Aggies in Austin, you know, and they were all there.
I said, no, it was a,
We were always pretty amazed at the number of people that would turn out, particularly Houston and Austin.
Do you have any special court trip memory or something?
No, I'm sure I do, but I can't think of any.
Let's do a football Saturday here.
Describe what it was like for you as a student.
What did you do when?
Well, your date would usually come in on Friday, and they'd figure out how to get their
selves here and come to your dormitory, be screamed at properly by all the people hanging out the windows and stuff.
And then probably, oh, maybe a dance or something like that that was some student sponsored event.
Usually a concert.
We had great concerts.
I mean, MSC put on really good concerts with Chris Christopherson.
Whoever was hot at the time was always here.
And so it was pretty easy to get a date to come see the Beach Boys or come see somebody that was playing at the time.
And we'd usually go to that.
And then Saturdays were pretty hectic because you had to do the core stuff too.
What time did those Saturdays begin?
Oh, it was 6.
I mean, you know, because you had to do all the core stuff.
The rooms had to be sparkling because all the parents and dates and all were going to be coming up there, so everything had to be just right and had to be inspected and all this kind of stuff.
Uniforms had to be perfect.

and then you know the depending on the time of the game your dates would come in and then you they would we would form up in the core behind the band and go to the stadium and our dates would walk along beside us and then go to our whatever seats we had and then we'd do the review inside and then go go to the seats and usually
Well, I guess usually after the game was generally when you had the concert.
It was usually Saturday night or something like that.
And Friday night would be midnight Yale practice and students, women students or whoever from other campuses always thought that was... And they were held in the stadium.
They were what?
Were they in the stadium then or...
See, earlier they'd been at the Y steps, but Midnight Yale practice was in the stadium.
In the stadium.
But all we did back then, we just filled up the horseshoe.
I mean, we didn't go like it does now.
My first Midnight Yale practice, Rick Peer and I ran out of the stadium.
Well, we were...
I'm sure we weren't drunk.
I'm sure we were just exuberant because it was our first minute of air practice.
For some reason we decided that we were going to go down on the field and we could be yell leaders too and we were going to help these people out.
They gently pushed us and then somebody threw an M-80 at us.
And so we crawled into, this is a terrible story, but we crawled into, remember they had grass at the time and those big old tubes that rolled the corks out?
We crawled into one of those.
Somebody thought that was lots of fun, so they threw an M-80 in there with us.
And when that thing went off, I mean, it just, it was just deafening.
And so we ran toward the other end of the field.
And we didn't see Rick until the game.
We don't know where he's been tonight.
But somehow I managed to find my way back.
But it was, I don't even remember our first shell practice.
Now, when you were a senior.
I was much better behaved when I was a senior.
Were you, your date in those days, is she your wife now?
No, I didn't meet her until later.
But when I was a senior, I was dating a girl that was an A&M student, Merrill Mitchell.
Describe what the student body president had to do on a football Saturday.
Did you have any?

Usually, yeah, usually had a little former student deal where the big money guys with the former student association would come in and they'd want the corps commander and the student body president to come say a few words about how, you know, how much we appreciate their support and it was a, you guys are doing great and I give more money kind of deal.
And I spent a lot of time doing that.
I would, on weekends,
They'd fly me to Tyler to go speak to the Tyler A&M Club, which is a pretty neat deal for a kid from Placido.
They're putting you on a King Air with your date and sending you to Tyler to go speak to a bunch of wealthy former students about why they need to keep giving to A&M.
And so I did a bunch of that, particularly on weekends and stuff like that.
But on a football weekend...
It was like every Saturday morning, bright and early, a breakfast deal with the Association of Former Students.

Buck Wires would have some deal for me to go speak to, and then after the game, there'd be another gathering of former students somewhere, and I'd go by there, generally with the Corps commander and the civilian student president, and show them what clean-cut kids we were.
Then where did you stand during the game?
Which students?
You were in the students.
Was there a reserved seat for the student body president?
No.
And then after the game... Our parents got pretty good seats.
After the game, were things kind of relaxed for you?
Yeah, nothing to do.
Sometimes Sunday morning there'd be another bleary-eyed speech.
And your senior year is the fall of 71.
Fall of 71, graduated May of 72.
And we didn't do well in football that year, did we?
Was that Emory's first year?
Yeah, I don't think we did well four years that I was there.
I mean, we started kissing our dates on first downs.
And Gene Stallings was the coach during most of that.
Most of the time, and Emory Ballard after that.
Let's see.
Describe going to basketball games in G. Raleigh in those days.
Dangerous.
dangerous if you were the opposing team and you did a layup.

See back in those days they would seat Billy Hobbs and all these guys right under the baskets and so if a guy from Baylor comes up and does a layup and they push him into the crowd I mean it was not a good deal.
I mean they'd beat the hell out of him five or six times before they sent him back on the field
And it was, I mean, that was a common deal.
I don't know if they still do that or not, but that seating was very close, and it seemed like almost every game something broke out in the D.O.U.
And the team was winning.
Basketball was doing good.
That's what I mean.
Yeah, Shelby.
And it was noisy.
Very noisy, big time, huge noise.
Were there any favorite opponents?
We had a real serious hate for Rice during the four years that I was there.
Rice was always, you know, Rice little band made a picture of a fire hydrant one time and darn near emptied the football stadium.
People got so mad about that.
You know, Rice was not well loved at the time.
A&M traditions.
Silver taps.
Describe going to silver taps.
You said a member of your squadron died.
The first silver taps we had as fish was for the guy that lived next door to me, a guy named Tom Stein from Honda.

And so it was, I mean, I'm sure it was a moving experience for everybody that was there, but for those of us that had known this guy through fish camp and for maybe a month, it was a, boy, it was a real gut-wrenching deal.
But it stayed that way the whole time.
I mean, it almost, almost always, I mean, the school was small enough then where we almost always met that guy or girl, whoever it was.
And it probably happened five or six times during the year, a car wreck or
some deal like that.
And y'all always took it seriously?
Always seriously, eerily quiet, not a word.

Went back to our dormitories and if you had to study you had to put a black quilt over your deal to make sure and there was somebody in a corps walking around those dorms making sure that no light came out of those dorms until the morning.
Describe Bonfire your freshman year.
Well, bonfire freshman year, we were out in the woods.
And so we didn't get close to the stack.
We were out there.
Somebody was cutting the trees down.
We were cutting the branches off and then loading the stuff on the stick.
And so we stayed out in the woods for a week or whatever it was and never saw the bonfire in the daylight until the morning before it was built.
And we did that for the whole year.
four years, that was our job.
And it was held where?
Bonfire was located over on the other side of Duncan, over there.
And the shape of Bonfire in your years was about how many stacks high?
I think my senior year was one of the years where it was 107 feet.
Oh, that was one of the tall years.
Yeah, it was.
But we wrapped the...
